<br>
Below him, he could make out Centuri explaining the message she had found. It was hard to make out the exact conversations, but the winds carried the voices to him. Fergussen had been warned that trouble brewed on the horizon, and had heard rumors that treachery had been committed upon his allies. It was the rain that cried, and the wind that whispered, and the earth which trembled in fury that had led him here to see what truth there was to this all.<br>
<br>
As the conversations died, Fergussen noticed Thorvan step outside the Guild Hall. The tall barbarian slowly nodded his head once, his eyes scanning the mountain side slowly. Then his fingers traced the air and he disappeared. <br>
<br>
Fergussen stretched slowly and prepared himself. Tracking a trail as cold as this one was already was no easy task, even worse when magic was involved. But he was determined, he had promises to fulfill. He sniffed the wind and slowly made his way deeper into the mountains...<br>
