<br>
Fergussen had sent one more message to Thorvan, meerly stating that his agents had found out nothing more and that the trail was growing more and more dim. He knew better then to tell his friend what he intended to do.<br>
<br>
Slowly his breath came back to him and the dizzying feeling of vertigo subsided with the earth firmly under his feet again. In front of him sat a small alter, carved with symbols and writings of a time long ago. The wind seemed to die down as a icy voice whispered &quot;Why dost thou disturb us?&quot; what seemed like millions of other voices resounded the question, adding in their ownn sentiments.....&quot;why can not we suffer in peace?&quot;, &quot;make the pain end&quot; and so on and so forth. <br>
<br>
The voices forced their way into the rangers mind. Slowly he sank to a knee under the force of them...but refused to give in. Shakily, he spoke... &quot;I have come to seek a favor from you. I have come seeking the aid of the spirit of pain and suffering.&quot;<br>
<br>
The voices receeded from his mind...and a form slowly took shape next to the alter of Innoruk. &quot;You know the price to be paid for such as this that you ask of us mortal?&quot;<br>
<br>
Fergussen grimaced, but nodded. &quot;I do, and am willing to pay. Will you answer my question?&quot;<br>
<br>
The form ran its hand over the alter, and two shining mithril chalices appeared. &quot;First the payment, and then the answer mortal. Give to us of your essence so that the dark lord may be appeased....and we shall guide you on your path.&quot;<br>
<br>
The creature reached out and took Fergussen by his wrists, he did not struggle. It felt as if thousands of hands gripped him, as if the countless souls that made up the embodiment of pain and suffering were not in front of him as one single individual. Stabs of pain shot Fergussen's arms as the wraith placed his wrists above the chalice's. Slowly, his life's blood and energy poured out of the wounds in his wrists filling the chalices to overflowing.<br>
<br>
The wraith of pain and suffering released his arms then and the wounds slowly stopped their bleeding. Fergussen hastily wrapped the wounds to staunch them closed. The wraith turned to him and spoke in its haunting voice once more. &quot;Innoruk shall be pleased......what is thine question mortal?&quot;<br>
<br>
Fergussen spoke without hesitation, &quot;Where can I find the missing leader of the Blood Circle, Zarius Mistwalker.&quot; He spoke not another word. When dealing with a creature such as this, it was best to keep the questions simple and direct, less they expect further payment. <br>
<br>
Were Thorvan here, he would be beside himself with anger. For a shaman to deal with spirits such as these, there was much less danger. They were trained to do such. As a ranger, Fergussen dealt with spirits on a daily basis, but they were much different. The spirits of nature had no individuality to them, they were all encompassing of there aspect and held both peace and malice within them. None the less, from all he had learned from the large barbarian whom he called brother, Fergussen knew that he placed his own spirit at eternal risk by what he did now. <br>
<br>
The wraith chuckled in its myriad voices. One of the goblets disappeared from the altar. The wrait lifeted the other and dumped its contents into Fergussen's hands. A blood red stone was all that came out. &quot;If you wish to find this Zarius Mistwalker, simply find the other chalice. To the Plain of Hate you must travel. The master awaits your arrival Stormcaller, he awaits it very much.&quot; With that the spirit disipated, fleeing back into the winds that echoed through the chasm of the Hole. <br>
<br>
Fergussen stared at the Soulstone for a long time. His wrists throbbed from his wounds and he knew that these would leave more scars to remind him of the past. He had helped to interfere with many of Innoruk's dark schemes before, and had dispatched of many of his servants. The old blind seer who lived in the plains of karana had warned him he would come to terms with the dark god someday. The spirits of the wind had spoken to him of a blade which he would wield to battle the dark one.<br>
<br>
Slowly and cautiously, Fergussen Stormcaller began his treacherous climb back across the chasm. There would be time for all of that in the future. In his heart, a small part of him yearned to return to the forests and to distance himself far from the lord of hate's influence. Many a time in his youth the ranger had nearly been consumed by the flame of hatred while he waged his personal war against the gnolls of blackburrow. But that was behind him now.<br>
<br>
There was no turning back anymore, Fergussen realized. He had come to far to stop now. Besides, he had made promises...and he intended to keep them.<br>
