Deep into the fastness of the trees, she followed the whispering call, ignoring the path. Happily she let the forest sounds wash the tension and stress of the past few weeks away.  <br>
A snapped branch and scuffled footfall broke the stillness of the evening and she whirled, hand on swordhilt and ready to defend herself.<br>
Fergussen! With shock she took in the ranger's haggard appearance.  The trail-stained and torn vest, the sunken hollows in his eyes and the pinched look around his lips spoke of a horrendous trial of the spirit. What could possibly make Fergussen weary enough to stumble on a path he was able to run blindfolded? The feeling of forboding returned, twofold.  Then, her searching eyes spotted the blood-soaked rags around his wrists.  <br>
With a cry, she ran forward and took his hands into hers.  A brief, but fervent prayer to the Mother yielded that familar warmth and when she took her hands away, the bleeding gashes on his wrists were healed, fading to thin, white lines that in a few minutes would cease to exist at all.  Another prayer and some of the weariness lifted from his shoulders.<br>
He gave her a tired smile and offered to escort her back to Blood Circle's guild hall.<br>
On the way back, she listened to his story with a sinking heart.  The Plane of Hate!  For a moment, she was ready to charge off in rightious anger and wreak vengance upon those who brought harm to her new family; then common sense took over again.  Centuri shook her head. Her skills were insufficient.  At best, she would only get herself killed.  At worst, her inadequacies would take the lives of others as they tried to protect her.  She would not be able to go with the others to rescue Zarius.<br>
<br>
She left Fergussen at the door to the hall.  There would be others wanting to hear his tale.  Thorvan would most likely have a few choice words for the ranger about him endangering himself.<br>
<br>
She turned down the long, dark hallway leading to the armory, pausing in her room only long enough to select a whetstone, rag and a bottle of oil.  The armory door creaked in protest as she hauled it open.  The glitter of steel in the lantern light was a familiar and comforting sight.  As comforting in its own way as the deep forest.  For the rest of the evening and through tomorrow, she would sharpen weapons and check armor.  She made a mental note to check with the spell-casters to ensure they had all the components for their spells.<br>
 Her brothers and sisters would go into battle as well-prepared as she could make them.  As she worked, Centuri prayed that her efforts would keep most of them from dying.<br>
