It appears as if Itno is now alone in discovering our mutual enemy...perhaps it is time that I return from the solace I once sought and re-assume my birthright in order that our hapless mage might live again.<br>
<br>
&lt;&lt;The continual sword to shield strikes pound a discordant cadence that rings throughout the Halls of the Dead.  Soulshiver smiles, a truly horrific sight and one not often seen, as for the first time he understands the often expressed and more often ignored pleas of the Necromatic Guild's desire to seperate their chambers of Dark Arcane study from the practice grounds of young Knights in training.  With an audible sigh, Soulshiver re-collects himself and ponders anew the murders he has just commited.  The meditation does not come easily, for these murders had held a different feel and have shaken the core of the dedicated Knight sworn to blood.  He attempts to recapture the events that led to the life that he drank and the blood that he spilt in Innoruuks dread place of worship.  **&quot;Ssss-Soulshiver-rr?&quot; stammered the novice, &quot;S-sir?&quot; With a shock, Soulshiver came to his senses, &quot;My....sincere...apologies, young one.&quot;  With a grimace that tried to be a smile the novice stopped rubbing blood back to his throat and tried to look brave despite having been suspended in the air by a not fully awake Knight of Shadows who was but moments before lying prone and oblivious to any sound or touch. &quot;It has been some time since I've been able to catch some sleep...&quot;, Soulshiver said wrly. &quot;Understood, Dark One, forgive me for interupting your much needed rest&quot;, said the young novice with a voice filled with hero-worship.  Soulshiver inwardly sighed as he sought to somehow bring this young one to his conclusion, &quot;The intrusion, I'm sure, will be worth it.  Why then, would you be so willing to put your life in danger?&quot;  The novice gulped anew and quickly offered, &quot;The Priests of Hate are expecting a new shipment of Fier'dal slaves arriving from Faydwer and have requested the Hall of Dead's help in seeing them transfered....uh...safely from the hands of the Orcs to the examining pits.&quot;  Soulshiver grim visage turned more grim and the room dropped several degrees.  Noticing that his life was quickly approaching its critical end the novice quickly added, &quot;Master Dvrix knows that such duty is far below your station, Dark One, however your brother, Tyvlain, is among the Tier'dal escorts and has asked for you specifically.&quot;  The name of his brother took Soulshiver aback and the shock caused him to stop the incantation that would have stolen the novices strength.  Seeing his opprotunity, the novice started to edge for the door. &quot;Young one, tell Dvrix, that I will accept this duty, however he owes me a bottle of Rivervale's finest.&quot;  Soulshiver smiled as the novice fled after a hasty bow. &quot;Tyvlain...hmm...&quot;. ** &lt;&lt;Soulshiver shakes his head. No, no, further than that&gt;&gt; **Soulshiver does not offer a smile or any indication of greeting despite his brothers best efforts to garner any.  &quot;By the Gods these Orcs stink, how you put up with them is beyond me Tyvlain&quot;, Soulshiver said in his best Orcish.  None of the orcs hesitated or looked up from their work unloading the slaves as they swallowed the insult, trembling in their fear.  &quot;Now, now Soulshiver, let us be civil&quot;, Tyvlain said with his trademark grin.  &quot;Slaving his hardly civil, Tyvlain, and especially so when coupled with this vermin&quot;, Soulshiver replied sharply and  puncuated it by a kick to the green back side of an Orc wearing Crushbone colors.  &quot;Bah, it appears as if you were not as successful as you'd hoped Tyvlain, just a bunch of weakend gnomes, dwarves, and brownies.  Dvrix told me of some Fier'dal...&quot;  Tyvlain, smiling again, &quot;Ah, it was rumored that you've seen quite a bit of Fier'dal lately, Soul, and rumors upon rumors that you've aligned yourself with others than those of our...how should you say...Dark Persuasion?&quot;  Soulshiver hands tightend on the haft of his Wurmslayer, turning the knuckles white.  &quot;Tyvlain, brother, you tread on ground that will be not your liking.&quot;  Tyvlain smiled with an even larger grin, &quot;So it is true, Mother will not take this news lightly.  Soul, Father was right, you were meant to be a Knight despite what Mother had said, you haven't an aristocratic bone in your body.  You are an open book...Still I perfer it that way, it simply means that I will be the next Duke of the Dark all the more sooner.... upon your demise, of course.&quot;  Soulshiver, had long since stopped listening to his brothers common litany as he noticed for the first time the promised Fier'dal stepping onto the shadowed dock.  They were ragged, wasted, starved and half-dead, yet hauntlngly familiar.  The male High Elf, even in his dazed condition took great pains to see that the female made it to the docks with safety.  Tyvlain, seeing his immediate charges landed, tossed a bag of coins carelessy to the Orcan Captain, &quot;Your payment, Grloss, a pleasure doing business with you.&quot;  Grloss unashamedly opened the bag and upon veiwing its contents smiled.  In his guttural tounge he called his men and together made their way out of the dank caves from the underbelly of Neriaks 3rd Gate.** &lt;&lt;Further,,,&gt;&gt;<br>
<br>
**In Innoruuk's Dread halls the slaves were seperated as to their importance of study.  The Fier'dal had captured the interest some Masters of the Dark Arts and they had sequestered them at the pinnacle of the Dark Temple.  Soulshiver had already said good-bye to his power craved brother and was heading back to the Hall when he heard horrific screams in the High Elven tongue raining down from the Temple.  Such screams were common here, but for some inexplicable reason, Soulshiver had to investigate.  There was something too familiar about that couple.  With little effort Soulshiver bounded upstairs unimpeded by the many guards stationed along the way.  Upon reaching the doors, the Skeletal pets of the Masters inside the room stood as silent sentinals as Soulshiver tried the door and found it un-locked.  Inside was an image that remains hard to re-conjure.  Upon a table laid the male Elf, with closer inspection it was easily apparent to see that he had once been a Paladin of Tunare.  Tunare's bright blazon was clear to see upon his heaving chest.  The female Elf was on a rack upright on a wall with a gnomish appearing device on her head that was enabling her to heal her companion.  It seemed odd to Soulshiver that he would be in so much pain, for it was more apparent than the male's paladinship that she was a Cleric of Tunare of significant skill.  It was then that he noticed the Necromancers taking turns on the male deliberately casting new found spells to judge their effects on a reliable continually healthy victim.  Scribes copied with much interest as each spell was catalogued.  The female form already impassioned by the torturing of her compainion begin to kick and cry out while at the same time growing noticeably weaker and weaker.  The prayers of healing were coming much slower and with much less fervor. It was obivious to Soulshiver now that the device placed on her enabled her to convert her own lifeforce for mana and she was dying as she continued to struggle to save the hapless paladin.  She then at a moment of infinite weakness said, &quot;I'm sorry,  my love, I can do no more...I shall wait for thee at Tunare's feet.&quot;  With a final momentous effort she prayed her last prayer and the chains once held taught with anger, hung slack with the wieght of her slack body.  The male, to his credit, ripped his right arm free mancle, chain, and all.  With an anguished cry, he whipped the chain with maniacal force cleaving completly the skull of the Necromancer nearest him. Almost as immediantly, the crazed, demonized pets of the Dark Masters burst through the door and swarmed the male in a frenzy and flurry that few can survive. Remarkably, calling upon the wrath of Tunare and weilding the chain with remarkable skill he fought and slew 2 of the 3 pets before succumbing to the onslaught of the battering undead hands and the dreaded chants of the Dark Masters.  Upon his dying breath, with a smile to the likes Soulshiver had never seen, he whispered, &quot;My wife, my Kannushi, my Centuri, I am coming...&quot;<br>
<br>
It was then that Soulshiver realized this cosmic irony.  Here, laid to rest at last, was the answers for all for which he'd been seeking.  Without an uttered cry, Soulshiver tore the undead monstrosity before him apart.  The pet, for the which I still have no explanation, looked surprised as it died.  The two remaing Dark Masters, looked almost white as they realized that they too would be dying today.  Out of Arcane essense, they could only scream as Soulshiver drank deeply their stolen life-forces and watch their headless corpses sink to the ground from the vantage point that Soulshiver's Wurmslayer had provided them.  The scribe, only wet-himself in fear and did not think to beg for mercy until after he had been tossed from the Temple's lofty station.  Soulshiver, once again in control of himself hastily gathered himself into the shadows and made ready his alibi.  His brother was wrong, he could play the game of the aristocrats, and he'll prove it.**  <br>
<br>
&lt;&lt;Master Dvrix muttered curses echo'ed again on the training courtyards re-awakening Soulshiver from his trance.  Quietly, he shouldered his pack, shield, and Wurmslayer determined to get answers.  For the one thing Soulshiver remembered most vividly, was as his heavy blade swung in its deadly arc to take the life of the last necromancer, the Dark master whipered, &quot;Blood Circle will fall, Soulshiver...and it will be accomplished by one whom ye call Brother.&quot;<br>
<br>
